  import LanguageTabs from "$lib/components/LanguageTabs.svelte";
</script>

Now let's close the loop and have our service publish events. We will emit an `Orders.Shipped` event so downstream services, such as a warehouse system, notifications service, or billing system, can react without being coupled directly to us.

<LanguageTabs>
{#snippet ts()}

Add the event schema to `schemas.ts`:

```ts
export const OrderShippedEvent = Type.Object({
  orderId: Type.String(),
  customerId: Type.String(),
  shippedAt: Type.String({ format: "date-time" }),
});
export type OrderShippedEvent = Static<typeof OrderShippedEvent>;
```

Register the event in `contracts/orders_service.ts`:

```ts
import * as schemas from "../schemas.ts";

// ...

// In the first defineServiceContract argument:
{ schemas }

// In the returned contract body:
  events: {
    "Orders.Shipped": {
      version: "v1",
      event: ref.schema("OrderShippedEvent"),
      capabilities: { publish: ["service"], subscribe: ["service"] },
    },
  },
```

The `capabilities` here mean: only `service`-tier principals may publish or subscribe. Other services that list `Orders.Shipped` in their own `uses` blocks will receive the events automatically.

Now publish the event from `main.ts`. Here we call it after marking an order as fulfilled. You would do this wherever your fulfillment logic lives:

```ts
await service.event.orders.shipped.publish({
  orderId,
  customerId,
  shippedAt: new Date().toISOString(),
});
```

`event.orders.shipped.publish(...)` validates the payload against `OrderShippedEvent` before sending. If the shape is wrong, it returns a `Result.err(...)` rather than silently dropping the event.

{/snippet}
{#snippet rust()}

Add the schema and event declaration:

```rust
fn order_shipped_event_schema() -> Value {
    json!({
        "type": "object",
        "required": ["orderId", "customerId", "shippedAt"],
        "properties": {
            "orderId": { "type": "string" },
            "customerId": { "type": "string" },
            "shippedAt": { "type": "string", "format": "date-time" }
        }
    })
}

.schema("OrderShippedEvent", order_shipped_event_schema())
.event(
    "Orders.Shipped",
    trellis_contracts::event("v1", "events.v1.Orders.Shipped", "OrderShippedEvent")
        .with_publish_capabilities(["service"])
        .with_subscribe_capabilities(["service"]),
)
```

After prepare, the generated SDK exposes an event type and descriptor. Add a publisher to `AppContext` so handler code can publish through shared context:

```rust
use trellis_rs::service::EventPublisher;

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct AppContext {
    pub orders: NatsKvResourceClient,
    pub publisher: EventPublisher,
}
```

Create it from the authenticated NATS client:

```rust
let context = Arc::new(AppContext {
    orders,
    publisher: service.event_publisher(),
});
```

Publish from your fulfillment logic:

```rust
use trellis_sdk_orders_service::events::OrdersShippedEventDescriptor;
use trellis_sdk_orders_service::types::OrderShippedEvent;

context
    .publisher
    .publish::<OrdersShippedEventDescriptor>(&OrderShippedEvent {
        order_id,
        customer_id,
        shipped_at: now_iso(),
    })
    .await?;
```

The publisher serializes through the generated event descriptor before sending to NATS.

{/snippet}
</LanguageTabs>

Upgrade the contract and restart.
